listitem.para:
If, for example, the default value ('input') is
      used, and one sets gp_inputs  = ['a.csv',
      'b.csv'], then the gnuplot script will see variables
      input1 and input2 as bellow

         input1 = "a.csv";
         input2 = "b.csv"; 

      and the plotting code may use them as follows

         plot input1 with lines, \
              input2 with points; 

      If we set GPLPOTINVAR = 'foo' in
      SConscript however, the script will see

         foo1 = "a.csv";
         foo2 = "b.csv";

If, for example, the default value ("output") is
      used, and one sets gp_outputs  = ['a.eps',
      'b.tex' ], then the gnuplot script will see the variables

         output1 = "a.eps";
         output2 = "b.tex"; 

      and the plotting code may use them as follows

         set output output1;
         # ...
         set output output2; 

      If we set GPLPOTOUTVAR = 'foo' in
      SConscript however, the script will see

         foo1 = "a.eps";
         foo2 = "b.tex";

If, for example, the default value ('eoutput') is
      used, and one sets gp_extoutputs  = ['a.eps',
      'b.eps' ], then the gnuplot script will see the variables

         eoutput1 = "a.eps";
         eoutput2 = "b.eps"; 

      If we set GPLOTEOUTVAR = 'foo' in
      SConscript however, the script will see

         foo1 = "a.eps";
         foo2 = "b.eps";

In case of dictionary, it should be a dict of the form { 'placeholder' : file }, where the placeholder is the placeholder used in gnuplot script instead of file name. The file is either string containing file name, or SCons node object. If, for example, the gp_inputs is a dictionary as below
{ 'a' : "input_a.csv", 'b: : "input_b.csv" }
then the file names are passed to the gnuplot script(s) via command line options, and are visible as if they were defined by
a = "input_a.csv"; b = "input_b.csv";
in the script(s). The script may then use placeholders a and b as below
plot a with lines, \ b with points;

In case of dictionary, it should be a dict of the form { 'placeholder' : file }, where the placeholder is the placeholder used in gnuplot script instead of file name. The file is either string containing file name, or SCons node object. If, for example, the gp_outputs is a dictionary as below
{ 'a' : "output_a.png", 'b: : "output_b.png" }
then the file names are passed to the gnuplot script(s) via command line options, and are visible as if they were defined by
a = "output_a.png"; b = "output_b.png";
in the script(s). The script may then use placeholders a and b as below
set output a; # ... set output b;

In the case of dictionary, it should be a dict of the form { 'placeholder' : file }, where the placeholder is the placeholder used in gnuplot script instead of file name. The file is either string containing file name, or SCons node object. If, for example, the gp_extoutputs is a dictionary as below
{ 'a' : "eout_a.eps", 'b: : "eout_b.eps" }
then the file names are passed to the gnuplot script(s) via command line options, and are visible as if they were defined by
a = "eout_a.epd"; b = "eout_b.eps";
in the script(s).
